                    <div class="section" id="key_definitions">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>KEY DEFINITIONS</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>DIVERSITY</h4><div><p><strong>Diversity</strong> refers to the presence of <em>differences</em> within a group or organisation.</p>

<p>This includes visible differences such as:</p>
<ul>
<li>Age, gender, ethnicity, and physical ability</li>
</ul>

<p>And less visible differences like:</p>
<ul>
<li>Educational background, life experiences, thinking styles, and beliefs</li>
</ul>

<div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 15px;">
<p><strong>Workplace Example:</strong><br>
A project team includes members from different departments, age groups, and cultural backgrounds. This mix of perspectives helps the team spot blind spots and develop more creative solutions.</p>
</div></div></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>EQUITY</h4><div><p><strong>Equity</strong> means ensuring that everyone has access to the same <em>opportunities</em> ‚Äî while recognising that people may need <em>different support</em> to get there.</p>

<p>Equity acknowledges that people start from different places and face different barriers. It's about levelling the playing field, not just treating everyone the same.</p>

<div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 15px;">
<p><strong>Workplace Example:</strong><br>
A manager notices that one team member struggles in large meetings but excels in smaller settings. Rather than forcing everyone into the same format, the manager offers alternative ways to contribute ‚Äî like one-to-one check-ins or written input before discussions.</p>
</div></div></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>INCLUSION</h4><div><p><strong>Inclusion</strong> is about creating an environment where every person feels <em>valued</em>, <em>respected</em>, and able to <em>contribute fully</em>.</p>

<p>Having a diverse team isn't enough if some voices are ignored, dismissed, or overlooked. Inclusion ensures that diversity is more than a headcount ‚Äî it's about belonging.</p>

<div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 15px;">
<p><strong>Workplace Example:</strong><br>
During a team brainstorm, a leader actively invites quieter members to share their thoughts and ensures no one dominates the conversation. Afterward, they follow up individually to capture any additional ideas. This creates a space where everyone feels heard.</p>
</div></div></div></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
                            <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="nextSection()">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="section" id="knowledge">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>EQUITY VS EQUALITY</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p>These two terms are often confused, but they mean very different things in practice.</p></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="comparison-box">
<div class="comparison-item equality">
<h5>Equality</h5>
<p>Giving <strong>everyone the same</strong> resources, support, or opportunities ‚Äî regardless of their individual circumstances.</p>
<p style="margin-top: 10px; color: #666; font-size: 14px;"><em>Example: Everyone receives the same training materials and the same amount of time to complete a task.</em></p>
</div>
<div class="comparison-item equity">
<h5>Equity</h5>
<p>Giving people what they <strong>need</strong> to have an equal chance of success ‚Äî which may mean different things for different people.</p>
<p style="margin-top: 10px; color: #666; font-size: 14px;"><em>Example: A team member with dyslexia receives audio versions of training materials and extra time, while others receive standard resources.</em></p>
</div>
</div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>WHY EQUALITY ALONE CAN BE UNFAIR</h4><div><p>On the surface, treating everyone the same sounds fair. But when people start from different positions or face different obstacles, identical treatment can actually <em>widen</em> gaps rather than close them.</p>

<p><strong>Consider this:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>A new starter with no industry experience and a 10-year veteran both receive the same onboarding ‚Äî but only one truly understands the context.</li>
<li>A parent with caring responsibilities and a colleague with no dependents are both expected to attend 8am meetings ‚Äî but only one has flexibility.</li>
<li>A team member working remotely in a different time zone is given the same deadlines as those in the office ‚Äî but has fewer hours of overlap for collaboration.</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Equality asks:</strong> "Are we giving everyone the same thing?"<br>
<strong>Equity asks:</strong> "Are we giving everyone what they need to succeed?"</p></div></div></div></div>

<div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>EQUITY IN DAY-TO-DAY LEADERSHIP</h4><div><p>As a leader or team member, practising equity means paying attention to individual needs and adjusting your approach accordingly. Here are some examples:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Flexible meeting formats:</strong> Offering multiple ways to contribute (verbal, written, asynchronous) so different communication styles are supported.</li>
<li><strong>Tailored development:</strong> Recognising that team members may need different types of coaching, mentoring, or stretch assignments based on their goals and gaps.</li>
<li><strong>Fair workload distribution:</strong> Accounting for personal circumstances (like caring responsibilities or health needs) when assigning tasks or setting deadlines.</li>
<li><strong>Accessibility considerations:</strong> Ensuring that tools, spaces, and resources are accessible to everyone ‚Äî not just the majority.</li>
<li><strong>Sponsorship and visibility:</strong> Actively advocating for team members who may be overlooked for opportunities due to bias or lack of visibility.</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-top: 15px;"><em>Equity doesn't mean lowering standards ‚Äî it means removing unnecessary barriers so everyone can meet those standards.</em></p></div></div></div></div></div>
                        <div class="navigation-buttons">
                            <button class="nav-btn" onclick="previousSection()">Previous</button>
                            <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="nextSection()">Continue</button>
